JUMIA will start selling Xiaomi telephones in the country after signed a partnership deal with the Chinese electronics company, Xiaomi Corporation. The deal will enable Jumia to open stores in the country that would store Xiaomi products mainly smartphone under Mi series. The Jumia Tanzania’s Chief Executive Officer Mr Zadok Prescott said through the partnership, Jumia would open Xiaomi stores and give access to millions of online customers in the country and across 13 other African countries. “This partnership is very important for us in Tanzania, as it will definitely foster the smartphone adoption in Africa as well as support e-commerce penetration,” Mr Prescott said yesterday. The partnership would be supported by an ambitious joint-marketing plan that covers this year, leveraging Jumia’s digital assets and Xiaomi marketing capabilities. Xiaomi is one of the leading Chinese smartphone producers based in Beijing. It also makes tablets, laptops, wearable devices, TVs, routers and other smartphone devices. “Xiaomi and Jumia have very similar internet DNA and will serve a common purpose,” he said. The Xiaomi Africa Senior Vice President, Wang Xiang, Senior said smartphone penetration in Africa stood at approximately 36 per cent in last year and the number expected to reach about 66 per cent by 2025. “We believe that working with Jumia will help us bring innovation for everyone across the continent,” said Wang. According to Wang, the firm is currently the world’s fourth-largest smartphone brand, and has established the world’s largest consumer Internet of Things (IoT) platform. Currently, Xiaomi products are present in more than 80 countries and regions worldwide and have a leading footing in many markets.